      <body>
      <pb n="35"/>
      <div type="article" xml:id="article">
         <cb n="1" rend="left_side"/>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
            <head n="1">This is the Famous Book of Sībawayh on naħw 'Grammar' and its Name is ʔal-kitāb 'The Book'</head>
               <p><name type="article's_author">Solomon Sara</name>, S.J. Georgetown University</p>
               <div type="book">
                  <p>In the Name of God the most merciful and the most compassionate. From him we seek help.</p>
                  <div type="chapter" n="I:1">
                     <head n="2">Chapter 1. This is bāb 'a chapter' on the ʕilm 'science': What are the Words of Arabic</head>
                     <p corresp="#article">(<bibl><editor>Bulaq</editor> <biblScope unit="volume">vol. 1.</biblScope> <biblScope unit="page">P.2</biblScope></bibl>,
                     <bibl><editor>Derenbourg</editor> <biblScope unit="volume">vol.1</biblScope> <biblScope unit="page">p.1</biblScope></bibl>,
                     <bibl><editor>Haruwn</editor> <biblScope unit="volume">vol.1</biblScope> <biblScope unit="page">p.12</biblScope></bibl>)<note xml:id="note_1" type="footnote" n="1">1</note></p>

                     <p>Words are: <term xml:lang="ar">ʔism</term> 'name', <term xml:lang="ar">fiʕl</term> 'action', and <term xml:lang="ar">ħarf</term> 'particle'<note xml:id="note_2" type="footnote" n="2">2</note>.
                     Particle <term xml:lang="ar">gāʔa limaʕnah</term> ‘has meaning’. It is neither <term xml:lang="ar">ʔism</term> ‘a name’ nor <term xml:lang="ar">fiʕl</term>
                     ' an action'. <term xml:lang="ar">ʔism</term> ‘name’<note xml:id="note_3" type="footnote" n="3">3</note> is: <term xml:lang="ar">ragulun</term> 'man’, <term xml:lang="ar">farasun</term> ‘horse’
                     <term xml:lang="ar">ħāʔiţun</term> ‘ wall' . As for <term xml:lang="ar">fiʕl</term> 'action' , examples were taken from the <term xml:lang="ar">lafđ</term>
                     'expression' for the <term xml:lang="ar">ʔalfāđ</term> 'events' of the <term xml:lang="ar">ʔasmāʔ</term> 'names', and were constructed for what maďā ‘has passed,
                     what <term xml:lang="ar">yakuwnu</term> ‘is to be’ but has not <term xml:lang="ar">yaɢaʕ</term> ‘happened’, and for what is <term xml:lang="ar">kāʔin</term>
                     ‘existent’ and has not <term xml:lang="ar">yanɢaţiʕ</term> ‘ceased’. As for the structure of what <term xml:lang="ar">maďā</term> ‘has passed’, it is:
                     <term xml:lang="ar">ðahaba</term> 'he went', <term xml:lang="ar">samiʕa</term> 'he heard', <term xml:lang="ar">makuθa</term> 'he remained', and 
                     <term xml:lang="ar">ħumida</term> 'he was thanked'. As for the structure of what has not <term xml:lang="ar">yaɢaʕ</term> ‘happened’, it is, as your statement
                     in giving a command: <term xml:lang="ar">ʔiðhab</term> 'go!', <term xml:lang="ar">ʔuɢtul</term> 'kill!', <term xml:lang="ar">ʔiďrib</term> 'hit!', and 
                     <term xml:lang="ar">muxbiran</term> 'predicating’:(L.5) <term xml:lang="ar">yaɢtulu</term> 'he kills'<note xml:id="note_4" type="footnote" n="4">4</note>, <term xml:lang="ar">yaðhabu</term> 'he goes', 
                     <term xml:lang="ar">yaďribu</term> 'he hits', <term xml:lang="ar">yuɢtalu</term> 'he is killed', and <term xml:lang="ar">yuďrabu</term> 'he is hit'. Similarly 
                     is the structure of what has not <term xml:lang="ar">yanɢaţiʕ</term> ‘ceased’ and is still <term xml:lang="ar">kāʔin</term> ‘existent’, if you were
                     to predicate about it. These <term xml:lang="ar">ʔamθilah</term> ‘examples’ are taken from the <term xml:lang="ar">lafđ</term> 'expression' for the 
                     <term xml:lang="ar">ʔaħdāθ</term> 'events' of the <term xml:lang="ar">ʔasmāʔ</term> 'names', and they have many structures which will be explained, God 
                     willing. As for <term xml:lang="ar">ʔaħdāθ</term> 'events', examples are: <term xml:lang="ar">ʔal-ďarb</term> 'the hit', <term xml:lang="ar">ʔal-ɢatl</term> 
                     'the kill', and <term xml:lang="ar">ʔal-ħamd</term> 'the praise'.</p>
                     <pb n="36"/><p>As for what has meaning but is neither <term xml:lang="ar">ʔism</term> ‘a name’ nor <term xml:lang="ar">fiʕl</term> ' an action' they are such as:
                     <term xml:lang="ar">θumma</term> 'then', <term xml:lang="ar">sawfa</term> 'future marker', <term xml:lang="ar">wāw ʔal-qasam</term> '[w] of oath',
                     <term xml:lang="ar">lām</term> ‘[l]’ of <term xml:lang="ar">ʔal-ʔiďāfah</term> ‘annexion’, and similar ones.<note xml:id="note_5" type="footnote" n="5">5</note></p>
                  </div>
               </div>
         </div>
         <cb n="2" xml:lang="ar" rend="right_side"/>
         <div type="original_text" xml:lang="ar">
            <head n="3">هذا كتاب سيبويه المشهور في نحو واسمه الكتاب</head>
            <div type="book">
               <p>بسم الله الرحمن الرحيم وبه نستعين</p>
               <div type="chapter" n="I:1">
                  <head n="4"> هذا باب علم ما الكَلِمُ من العربية (١)</head>
                  <p>فالكَلِمُ: اسمٌ، وفِعْلٌ، وحَرْفٌ جاء لمعنى ليس باسم ولا فعل فالاسمُ رجلٌ، وفرسٌ وحائطٌ وأما الفعل فأمثلةٌ أُخذتْ من لفظ أحداث الأسماء وُبنيتْ لما مضى ولما يكون ولم يقع،
                   وما هو كائن لم يَنقطع فأما بناء ما مضى فذَهَبَ وسَمِعَ ومَكُثَ وحُمِدَ. وأما بناء ما لم يقع فإنه قولك آمِراً اذهَبْ واقتُلْ واضرِبْ، ومخبِراً يَقْتُلُ ويَذهَبُ ويَضرِبُ ويَقتُلُ ويُضْرَبُ.
                   .وكذلك بناء ما لم يَنقطع وهو كائن إذا أَخبرتَ فهذه الأمثلة التي أخذت من لفظ أحداث الأسماء، ولها أبنية كثيرة ستبين إن شاء الله والأحداث نحو الضَرْبِ والقَتْل الحَمْد</p>
                  <pb n="36"/><p>وأما ما جاء لمعنى وليس باسم ولا فعل فنحو ثُمَ وسَوْفَ وواوالقسم ولام الإضافة ونحو هذا.</p>
               </div>
            </div>
         </div>  
      </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <list type="list_of_footnotes">
            <item n="1"><note corresp="#note_1">1This translation will be based on Derenbourg’s edition of ʔal-kitāb as the base. All chapter, page and line numbers
            refer to this edition.</note></item>
            <item n="2"><note corresp="#note_2">2This tri-partite division will be elaborated on in the rest of ʔal-kitāb. Also to be mentioned is that a decision
            was made to be as faithful to the literal meaning of the terms as possible.</note></item>
            <item n="3"><note corresp="#note_3">3The way Sībawayh explains terms like ʔism 'name', fiʕl 'action', and ħarf 'particle', is by way of exemplification</note></item>
            <item n="4"><note corresp="#note_4">4This form may be glossed as ‘he is killing’.</note></item>
            <item n="5"><note corresp="#note_5">5At this early stage, the three classes of words are described both by what they are, names and events, with temporal indicators
            marking the variety of actions, and by what they are not with the particles being different from both names and names of events and the temporality of actions. Each
            class will be more fully attended to in the subsequent chapters.</note></item>
         </list>
         <div type="list_of_entries">
            <entry>
               <form type="lemma">
                  <orth>في</orth>
                  <pron notation="IPA">/fiː/</pron>
               </form>
               <gramGrp>
                  <pos>preposition</pos>
               </gramGrp>
               <sense n="1">
                  <def>Used to indicate location, inclusion, or position within spatial, temporal or other limits.</def>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>in, inside, within</quote>
                  </cit>
               </sense>
               <sense n="2">
                  <def>Used as a function word to indicate what is dealt with as the object of thought, feeling, or action.</def>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>of, about, in regards to, pertaining to, in the subject or topic of</quote>
                  </cit>
                  <cit type="example">
                     <quote>هذا كتاب سيبويه المشهور في نحو واسمه الكتاب</quote>
                  </cit>
               </sense>
            </entry>

            <entry>
               <form type="lemma">
                  <orth>فرس</orth>
                  <pron notation="IPA">/faras/</pron>
               </form>
               <gramGrp>
                  <pos>noun</pos>
               </gramGrp>
               <form type="inflected">
                  <orth>أفراس</orth>
                  <pron notation="IPA">/ʔafraːs/</pron>
                  <number>plural</number>
               </form>
               <sense n="1">
                  <def>a four-footed mammal with hooves, a mane, and a tail, used for riding and pulling carts, etc.</def>
                  <usg type="syn">حصان</usg>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>horse</quote>
                  </cit>
               </sense>
            </entry>

            <entry>
               <form type="lemma" xml:id="ism">
                  <orth>اسم</orth>
                  <pron notation="IPA">/ism/</pron>
               <gramGrp>
                  <pos>noun</pos>
               </gramGrp>
                  <form type="inflected">
                     <orth>أسماء</orth>
                     <pron notation="IPA">/ʔasmaːʔ/</pron>
                     <gramGrp>
                        <number>plural</number>
                     </gramGrp>
                  </form>
                  <form type="derivative" xml:id="ismiyy">
                     <orth>اسمي</orth>
                     <pron notation="IPA">/ismijj/</pron>
                     <gramGrp>
                        <pos>adjective</pos>
                     </gramGrp>
                  </form>
               </form>
               <sense n="1" corresp="#ism">
                  <def>a word or term by which a person or thing is known</def>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>name</quote>
                  </cit>
               </sense>
               <sense n="2" corresp="#ism">
                  <usg type="dom">grammar</usg>
                  <def>any of a class of words naming or denoting a person, thing, place, action, quality, etc.</def>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>noun</quote>
                  </cit>
               </sense>
               <sense n="3" corresp="#ismiyy">
                  <usg type="dom">grammar</usg>
                  <def>of or relating to a noun or noun phrase</def>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>nominal</quote>
                  </cit>
               </sense>
            </entry> 

            <entry>
               <form type="lemma" xml:id="daraba">
                  <orth>ضرب</orth>
                  <pron notation="IPA">/dˤaraba/</pron>
                  <gramGrp>
                     <pos>verb</pos>
                     <number expand="third person singular">3ps</number>
                     <gen>masculine</gen>
                     <tns>past</tns>
                  </gramGrp>
                  <form type="inflected">
                     <orth>اضرب</orth>
                     <pron notation="IPA">/idˤrib/</pron>
                     <gramGrp>
                        <number expand="second person singular">2ps</number>
                        <gen>masculine</gen>
                        <mood>imperative</mood>
                     </gramGrp>
                  </form>
                  <form type="inflected">
                     <orth>يضرب</orth>
                     <pron notation="IPA">jadˤribu</pron>
                     <gramGrp>
                        <number expand="third person singular">3ps</number>
                        <gen>masculine</gen>
                        <mood>indicative</mood>
                        <tns>present</tns>
                     </gramGrp>
                  </form>
                  <form type="derivative" xml:id="darb">
                     <orth>ضرب</orth>
                     <pron notation="IPA">dˤarb</pron>
                     <gramGrp>
                        <pos>noun</pos>
                     </gramGrp>
                  </form>
               </form>
               <sense n="1" corresp="#daraba">
                  <def>to deal (a blow or stroke) to (a person or thing)</def>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>to hit</quote>
                  </cit>
               </sense>
               <sense n="2" corresp="#darb">
                  <def>an act or instance of striking or forcefully coming in contact with someone or something</def>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>hit</quote>
                  </cit>
               </sense>
               <sense n="3" corresp="#darb">
                  <usg type="dom">grammar</usg>
                  <def>a manner, method, or means</def>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>way, manner, example</quote>
                  </cit>
                  <usg type="syn">نحو</usg>
               </sense>
            </entry>

            <entry>
               <form type="lemma">
                  <orth>نحو</orth>
                  <pron notation="IPA">/naħw/</pron>
               </form>
               <gramGrp>
                  <pos>noun</pos>
               </gramGrp>
               <sense n="1">
                  <def>the branch of linguistics that deals with syntax and morphology, sometimes also phonology and semantics</def>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>grammar</quote>
                  </cit>
               </sense>
               <sense n="2">
                  <usg type="dom">grammar</usg>
                  <def>a manner, method, or means</def>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>way, manner, example</quote>
                  </cit>
                  <usg type="syn">ضرب</usg>
               </sense>
            </entry>
         </div>
      </back> 
